  Session 12: Addressing the Skeptics

  CHEN: The kernel community will ask: "Why C++ when Rust exists?" The answer needs to be precise.

  TANAKA: Here's my pitch:

  Rust excels where ownership is clear and lifetimes are lexical. Filesystems, crypto, pure algorithms.

  Rust struggles where ownership is shared, dynamic, or externally controlled. Device models, networking stacks, scheduling.

  The kernel is 50% clear ownership (Rust fits), 50% shared mutable state (Rust fights).

  C++ with IRO-style safety offers:
  - Incremental adoption (no FFI boundary)
  - Familiar semantics (C with benefits)
  - Destructors that can observe and act (not just Drop)
  - No ownership model to escape when it doesn't fit

  The cost is manual discipline. The benefit is no unsafe escape hatch that the compiler ignores.

  PETROVA: I'd add: C++ is evolving. Contracts in C++26. Static analysis improving. Pattern matching coming. Rust is more static; C++ is catching up on safety while retaining flexibility.

  OKAFOR: The ARM perspective: Rust's stack usage is higher due to ownership-based error handling. Every Result<T, E> must be large enough for both variants. C++ expected with proper NRVO can return in registers. For hot paths, this matters.

  VOSS: The toolchain perspective: Clang compiles both C and C++. Same LTO, same PGO, same sanitizers. Adding C++ to a C kernel is a configuration flag. Adding Rust requires a parallel toolchain, with all the integration pain that implies.

